GETTING STARTED:

Generate HTML Assets: Hand-Coding OR Static Site Generators OR Frontend Framework

- - - - - - - - - -

Static Site Generator

Simply put, a static site generator is an application that takes your site content, applies it to templates, and generates a structure of purely static HTML files ready to be delivered to visitors.

Template + Contents > Compile > Website

* JAM Stack: (Javascript, API, Markup)
* Jekyll (Ruby)
* Hugo (Go)
* Gatsby (JavaScript)
* 11ty (JavaScript)
* Next.js

- - - - - - - - - -

Content Management

* headless CMSs - used only for "content management" tasks
* traditional CMSs - used also for templating and frontend styling.

* Forestry (Jekyll) (Hugo)
* DatoCMS
* Netlify CMS
* Contentful
* Headless WordPress
* Ghost
* Strapi
* Sanity.io

- - - - - - - - - -

Frontend Framework
* React
* Vue.js
* Preact

- - - - - - - - - -

Non-Technical

* Stackbit (With practically zero-configuration, you can bundle a static site generator with a headless CMS and deploy a website to Netlify)

- - - - - - - - - -

Dynamic Features

* Serverless(backend functions)
* StaticKit (backend functions)
* Netlify (identity, forms, and backend functions)
* Auth0 (identity)
* Algolia (search)
* Snipcart (e-commerce)
* CartQL (e-commerce)
* Disqus or Staticman (user-generated content)

CUSTOM FUCTIONS

* abstract own functions into reusable APIs
* AWS lambda functions
* netlify functions

CUSTOM DATA

* FaunaDB
* Serverless GraphQL

